// COM/ribbon/RTD destructive-teardown hook, registered with the lifecycle layer
// (xll::SetGracefulTeardownHook) at xlAutoOpen and invoked by
// xll::GracefulTeardownOnce() — which runs EXACTLY ONCE, on a CONFIRMED shutdown
// (RibbonAddIn::OnBeginShutdown / OnDisconnection), NEVER on a cancelled quit.
//
// These steps used to run eagerly inside xlAutoClose, which Excel calls BEFORE
// the Save/Cancel prompt — so a cancelled quit disconnected the ribbon and
// revoked the class object and the add-in could not recover. They now run only
// here, on a real teardown. This hook runs on the STA thread (the COM event
// thread), so ribbon loadImage callbacks (same thread) cannot be in flight.
//
// GracefulTeardownOnce() drains the command threads (WaitForCommandDrain) AFTER
// this hook returns and AFTER it has set g_isUnloading, so the drain is the one
// that closes the §23.0 UAF window; this hook only performs the COM disconnect /
// revoke / unregister that must live in this template TU.
//
// revokeRtdClassObject (AGENTS.md §23.6, close-time ghost fix): false on a HOST
// SHUTDOWN — we then SKIP CoRevokeClassObject(g_rtdCookie) so Excel can start +
// complete its own RTD ServerTerminate/DisconnectData handshake (an eager revoke
// here BLOCKS that handshake, leaving Excel windowless). true on an add-in
// DISABLE (session continues) — we still revoke so no stale factory lingers. The
// ribbon revoke/disconnect is unaffected by this flag.
static void GracefulComTeardownHook(bool revokeRtdClassObject) {
    
    
    // RTD teardown: we intentionally do NOT Release / delete the RtdServer
    // instance here (that instance is EXCEL-OWNED; touching it would double-free).
    // The post-delete g_phost fence is the JoinWorker() in
    // xll::GracefulTeardownOnce() (runs AFTER this hook), not this branch.
    //
    // CLOSE-TIME GHOST FIX (AGENTS.md §23.6, 2026-06-17). On a HOST SHUTDOWN we
    // deliberately SKIP CoRevokeClassObject(g_rtdCookie). Evidence (the Option-2
    // experiment): an eager revoke here BLOCKS Excel from STARTING its own RTD
    // shutdown handshake — with the revoke skipped Excel issues DisconnectData on
    // every live topic and (once the STA is pumped, see GracefulTeardownOnce)
    // delivers ServerTerminate, so Excel's RTD subsystem considers its topics torn
    // down and the process can exit instead of lingering windowless. The class
    // object is process-scoped: on a host shutdown the process is ending anyway,
    // so leaving it registered until DLL_PROCESS_DETACH (which unmaps everything)
    // is harmless — no new activation can resolve it after the host is gone.
    //
    // On an add-in DISABLE (ext_dm_UserClosed; revokeRtdClassObject == true) the
    // SESSION CONTINUES, so we MUST still revoke — otherwise a stale factory would
    // linger for the rest of the live session and a re-enable could resolve the
    // dead class object. The mode is threaded in from RibbonAddIn::OnDisconnection
    // / OnBeginShutdown via xll::GracefulTeardownOnce(isHostShutdown).
    if (g_rtdCookie != 0) {
        if (revokeRtdClassObject) {
            XLL_SAFE_BLOCK_BEGIN
                HRESULT hr = CoRevokeClassObject(g_rtdCookie);
                if (FAILED(hr)) {
                    SAFE_LOG_ERROR("CoRevokeClassObject failed: " + std::to_string(hr));
                } else {
                    SAFE_LOG_INFO("Revoked RTD Class Object (add-in disable / non-host-shutdown).");
                }
            XLL_SAFE_BLOCK_END_CONTINUE
            g_rtdCookie = 0;
        } else {
            // Host shutdown: keep the class object registered so Excel can start +
            // complete its RTD ServerTerminate/DisconnectData handshake. The cookie
            // is left non-zero on purpose; DLL_PROCESS_DETACH unmaps the factory.
            SAFE_LOG_INFO("RTD class object revoke SKIPPED on host shutdown (allow Excel to complete its RTD teardown handshake; see AGENTS.md §23.6).");
        }
    }
    
}


extern "C" __declspec(dllexport) int __stdcall xlAutoClose() {
    // NON-DESTRUCTIVE. Excel calls xlAutoClose BEFORE the "Save changes? /
    // Cancel" prompt on quit, and it is the ONLY callback that fires on a
    // CANCELLED quit. Doing the ribbon disconnect / CoRevokeClassObject /
    // registry unregister / drains / server kill HERE (as this template used to)
    // turned a cancelled quit into a zombie add-in (every UDF -> #VALUE!, ribbon
    // dead, server gone, no recovery). All of that destructive work now lives in
    // xll::GracefulTeardownOnce(), driven from the CONFIRMED-shutdown COM events
    // (RibbonAddIn::OnBeginShutdown / OnDisconnection) which never fire on a
    // cancelled quit, with DLL_PROCESS_DETACH + the Job's KILL_ON_JOB_CLOSE as
    // the universal backstop. The COM-specific destructive steps (disconnect /
    // revoke / unregister / GDI+ down) are registered as the teardown hook in
    // xlAutoOpen below (GracefulComTeardownHook). See AGENTS.md §20 and
    // docs/superpowers/specs/2026-06-13-cancel-quit-teardown-design.md.
    //
    // EXPERIMENT-GATED FOLLOW-UP (design §5 / §8 decision 2): if a real-Excel
    // experiment shows Excel UNREGISTERS this XLL's functions at xlAutoClose,
    // the documented follow-up is to re-register (re-run the xlfRegister loop)
    // from the first CalculationEnded after a cancelled xlAutoClose. NOT
    // implemented here (gated on the unrun experiment).
    return xll::OnAutoClose();
}









